#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:87
msgid ""
"Routinator collects and processes Resource Public Key Infrastructure "
"(RPKI) data. It validates the Route Origin Attestations contained in the "
"data and makes them available to your BGP routing workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:91
msgid ""
"It can either run in one-shot mode outputting a list of validated route "
"origins in various formats or as a server for the RPKI-to-Router (RTR) "
"protocol that routers often implement to access the data, or via HTTP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:95
msgid ""
"These modes and additional operations can be chosen via commands. For the"
" available commands, see `Commands`_ below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:99
msgid "Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:101
msgid "The available options are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:105
msgid ""
"Provides the path to a file containing basic configuration. If this "
"option is not given, Routinator will try to use "
":file:`$HOME/.routinator.conf` if that exists. If that doesn't exist, "
"either, default values for the options as described here are used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:110
msgid ""
"See `Configuration File`_ below for more information on the format and "
"contents of the configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:115
msgid ""
"Specifies the base directory to keep status information in. Unless "
"overwritten by the :option:`-r` or :option:`-t` options, the local "
"repository will be kept in the sub-directory repository and the TALs will"
" be kept in the sub-directory :file:`tals`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:120
msgid "If omitted, the base directory defaults to :file:`$HOME/.rpki-cache`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:124
msgid ""
"Specifies the directory to keep the local repository in. This is the "
"place where Routinator stores the RPKI data it has collected and thus is "
"a copy of all the data referenced via the trust anchors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:130
msgid ""
"Specifies the directory containing the trust anchor locators (TALs) to "
"use. Trust anchor locators are the starting points for collecting and "
"validating RPKI data. See `Trust Anchor Locators`_ for more information "
"on what should be present in this directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:137
msgid ""
"Provides the path to a local exceptions file. The option can be used "
"multiple times to specify more than one file to use. Each file is a JSON "
"file as described in :rfc:`8416`. It lists both route origins that should"
" be filtered out of the output as well as origins that should be added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:144
msgid ""
"If this option is present, the repository will be validated in strict "
"mode following the requirements laid out by the standard documents very "
"closely. With the current RPKI repository, using this option will lead to"
" a rather large amount of invalid route origins and should therefore not "
"be used in practice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:150
msgid "See `Relaxed Validation`_ below for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:154
msgid ""
"This option defines how deal with stale objects. In RPKI, manifests and "
"CRLs can be stale if the time given in their *next-update* field is in "
"the past, indicating that an update to the object was scheduled but "
"didn't happen. This can be because of an operational issue at the issuer "
"or an attacker trying to replay old objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:160
msgid ""
"There are three possible policies that define how Routinator should treat"
" stale objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:163
msgid ""
"A policy of *reject* instructs Routinator to consider all stale objects "
"invalid. This will result in all material published by the CA issuing "
"this manifest and CRL to be invalid including all material of any child "
"CA."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:167
msgid ""
"The *warn* policy will allow Routinator to consider any stale object to "
"be valid. It will, however, print a warning in the log allowing an "
"operator to follow up on the issue. This is the default policy if the "
"option is not provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:172
msgid ""
"Finally, the *accept* policy will cause Routinator to quietly accept any "
"stale object as valid."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:177
msgid ""
"As a precaution, Routinator will reject rsync and HTTPS URIs from RPKI "
"data with dubious host names. In particular, it will reject the name "
"*localhost*, host names that consist of IP addresses, and a host name "
"that contains an explicit port."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:182
msgid "This option allows to disable this filtering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:186
msgid "If this option is present, rsync is disabled and only RRDP will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:190
msgid ""
"Provides the command to run for rsync. This is only the command itself. "
"If you need to provide options to rsync, use the ``rsync-args`` "
"configuration file setting instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:194
msgid ""
"If this option is not given, Routinator will simply run rsync and hope "
"that it is in the path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:199
msgid ""
"Sets the number of seconds an rsync command is allowed to run before it "
"is terminated early. This protects against hanging rsync commands that "
"prevent Routinator from continuing. The default is 300 seconds which "
"should be long enough except for very slow networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:206
msgid "If this option is present, RRDP is disabled and only rsync will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:210
msgid ""
"Sets the timeout in seconds for any RRDP-related network operation, i.e.,"
" connects, reads, and writes. If this option is omitted, the default "
"timeout of 30 seconds is used. Set the option to 0 to disable the "
"timeout."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:216
msgid ""
"Sets the timeout in seconds for RRDP connect requests. If omitted, the "
"general timeout will be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:221
msgid ""
"If present,  sets the local address that the RRDP client should bind to "
"when doing outgoing requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:226
msgid ""
"This option provides a path to a file that contains a certificate in PEM "
"encoding that should be used as a trusted certificate for HTTPS server "
"authentication. The option can be given more than once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:230
msgid ""
"Providing this option does not disable the set of regular HTTPS "
"authentication trust certificates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:235
msgid ""
"This option provides the URI of a proxy to use for all HTTP connections "
"made by the RRDP client. It can be either an HTTP or a SOCKS URI. The "
"option can be given multiple times in which case proxies are tried in the"
" given order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:242
msgid ""
"If this option is present, unused files and directories will not be "
"deleted from the repository directory after each validation run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:247
msgid ""
"Sets the number of threads to distribute work to for validation. Note "
"that the current processing model validates trust anchors all in one go, "
"so you are likely to see less than that number of threads used throughout"
" the validation run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:254
