#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:510
msgid ""
"Specifies a local address and port to listen on for incoming RTR "
"connections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:513
msgid ""
"Routinator supports both protocol version 0 defined in :rfc:`6810` and "
"version 1 defined in :rfc:`8210`. However, it does not support router "
"keys introduced in version 1.  IPv6 addresses must be enclosed in square "
"brackets. You can provide the option multiple times to let Routinator "
"listen on multiple address-port pairs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:521
msgid ""
"Specifies the address and port to listen on for incoming HTTP "
"connections.  See `HTTP Service`_ below for more information on the HTTP "
"service provided by Routinator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:527
msgid ""
"The RTR listening socket will be acquired from systemd via socket "
"activation. Use this option together with systemd's socket units to allow"
" a Routinator running as a regular user to bind to the default RTR port "
"323."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:532
msgid ""
"Currently, all TCP listener sockets handed over by systemd will be used "
"for the RTR protocol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:537
msgid ""
"The amount of seconds the server should wait after having finished "
"updating and validating the local repository before starting to update "
"again. The next update will be earlier if objects in the repository "
"expire earlier. The default value is 600 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:544
msgid ""
"The amount of seconds to suggest to an RTR client to wait before trying "
"to request data again if that failed. The default value is 600 seconds, "
"as recommended in :rfc:`8210`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:550
msgid ""
"The amount of seconds to an RTR client can keep using data if it cannot "
"refresh it. After that time, the client should discard the data. Note "
"that this value was introduced in version 1 of the RTR protocol and is "
"thus not relevant for clients that only implement version 0. The default "
"value, as recommended in :rfc:`8210`, is 7200 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:559
msgid ""
"In RTR, a client can request to only receive the changes that happened "
"since the last version of the data it had seen. This option sets how many"
" change sets the server will at most keep. If a client requests changes "
"from an older version, it will get the current full set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:565
msgid ""
"Note that routers typically stay connected with their RTR server and "
"therefore really only ever need one single change set. Additionally, if "
"RTR server or router are restarted, they will have a new session with new"
" change sets and need to exchange a full data set, too. Thus, increasing "
"the value probably only ever increases memory consumption."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:572
msgid "The default value is 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:576
msgid ""
"States a file which will be used in daemon mode to store the processes "
"PID.  While the process is running, it will keep the file locked."
