#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:636
msgid "Trust Anchor Locators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:637
msgid ""
"RPKI uses trust anchor locators, or TALs, to identify the location and "
"public keys of the trusted root CA certificates. Routinator keeps these "
"TALs in files in the TAL directory which can be set by the  :option:`-t` "
"option. If the :option:`-b` option is used instead, the TAL directory "
"will be in the subdirectory *tals* under the directory specified in this "
"option. The default location, if no options are used at all is "
":file:`$HOME/.rpki-cache/tals`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:644
msgid ""
"This directory can be created and populated with the TALs of the five "
"Regional Internet Registries (RIRs) via the :command:`init` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:647
msgid ""
"If the directory does exist, Routinator will use all files with an "
"extension of *.tal* in this directory. This means that you can add and "
"remove trust anchors by adding and removing files in this directory. If "
"you add files, make sure they are in the format described by :rfc:`7730` "
"or the upcoming :rfc:`8630`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:656
msgid "Configuration File"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:657
msgid ""
"Instead of providing all options on the command line, they can also be "
"provided through a configuration file. Such a file can be selected "
"through the :option:`-c` option. If no configuration file is specified "
"this way but a file named :file:`$HOME/.routinator.conf` is present, this"
" file is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:662
msgid ""
"The configuration file is a file in TOML format. In short, it consists of"
" a sequence of key-value pairs, each on its own line. Strings are to be "
"enclosed in double quotes. Lists can be given by enclosing a comma-"
"separated list of values in square brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:667
msgid ""
"The configuration file can contain the following entries. All path values"
" are interpreted relative to the directory the configuration file is "
"located in. All values can be overridden via the command line options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:673
msgid "repository-dir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:672
msgid ""
"A string containing the path to the directory to store the local "
"repository in. This entry is mandatory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:677
msgid "tal-dir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:676
msgid ""
"A string containing the path to the directory that contains the Trust "
"Anchor Locators. This entry is mandatory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:681
msgid "exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:680
msgid ""
"A list of strings, each containing the path to a file with local "
"exceptions. If missing, no local exception files are used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:685
msgid "strict"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:684
msgid ""
"A boolean specifying whether strict validation should be employed. If "
"missing, strict validation will not be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:699
msgid "stale"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:688
msgid "A string specifying the policy for dealing with stale objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:693
msgid "reject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:691
msgid ""
"Consider all stale objects invalid rendering all material published by "
"the CA issuing the stale object to be invalid including all material of "
"any child CA."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:696
msgid "warn"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:696
msgid "Consider stale objects to be valid but print a warning to the log."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:699
msgid "accept"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:699
msgid "Quietly consider stale objects valid."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:703
msgid "allow-dubious-hosts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:702
msgid ""
"A boolean value that, if present and true, disables Routinator's "
"filtering of dubious host names in rsync and HTTPS URIs from RPKI data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:706
msgid "disable-rsync"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:706
msgid "A boolean value that, if present and true, turns off the use of rsync."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:710
msgid "rsync-command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:709
msgid ""
"A string specifying the command to use for running rsync. The default is "
"simply *rsync*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:719
msgid "rsync-args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:713
msgid ""
"A list of strings containing the arguments to be passed to the rsync "
"command. Each string is an argument of its own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:716
msgid ""
"If this option is not provided, Routinator will try to find out if your "
"rsync understands the ``--contimeout`` option and, if so, will set it to "
"10 thus letting connection attempts time out after ten seconds. If your "
"rsync is too old to support this option, no arguments are used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:724
msgid "rsync-timeout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:722
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying the number seconds an rsync command is "
"allowed to run before it is being terminated. The default if the value is"
" missing is 300 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:727
msgid "disable-rrdp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:727
msgid "A boolean value that, if present and true, turns off the use of RRDP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:733
msgid "rrdp-timeout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:730
msgid ""
"An integer value that provides a timeout in seconds for all individual "
"RRDP-related network operations, i.e., connects, reads, and writes. If "
"the value is missing, a default timeout of 30 seconds will be used. Set "
"the value to 0 to turn the timeout off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:737
msgid "rrdp-connect-timeout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:736
msgid ""
"An integer value that, if present, sets a separate timeout in seconds for"
" RRDP connect requests only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:741
msgid "rrdp-local-addr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:740
msgid ""
"A string value that provides the local address to be used by RRDP "
"connections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:747
msgid "rrdp-root-certs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:744
msgid ""
"A list of strings each providing a path to a file containing a trust "
"anchor certificate for HTTPS authentication of RRDP connections. In "
"addition to the certificates provided via this option, the system's own "
"trust store is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:752
msgid "rrdp-proxies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:750
msgid ""
"A list of string each providing the URI for a proxy for outgoing RRDP "
"connections. The proxies are tried in order for each request. HTTP and "
"SOCKS5 proxies are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:758
msgid "dirty"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:755
msgid ""
"A boolean value which, if true, specifies that unused files and "
"directories should not be deleted from the repository directory after "
"each validation run.  If left out, its value will be false and unused "
"files will be deleted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:763
msgid "validation-threads"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:761
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying the number of threads to be used during "
"validation of the repository. If this value is missing, the number of "
"CPUs in the system is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:767
msgid "log-level"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:766
msgid ""
"A string value specifying the maximum log level for which log messages "
"should be emitted. The default is warn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:788
msgid "log"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:770
msgid ""
"A string specifying where to send log messages to. This can be one of the"
" following values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:776
msgid "default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:774
msgid ""
"Log messages will be sent to standard error if Routinator stays attached "
"to the terminal or to syslog if it runs in daemon mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:779
msgid "stderr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:779
msgid "Log messages will be sent to standard error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:782
msgid "syslog"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:782
msgid "Log messages will be sent to syslog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:786
msgid "file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:785
msgid ""
"Log messages will be sent to the file specified through the log-file "
"configuration file entry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:788
msgid "The default if this value is missing is, unsurprisingly, default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:793
msgid "log-file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:791
msgid ""
"A string value containing the path to a file to which log messages will "
"be appended if the log configuration value is set to file. In this case, "
"the value is mandatory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:797
msgid "syslog-facility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:796
msgid ""
"A string value specifying the syslog facility to use for logging to "
"syslog. The default value if this entry is missing is daemon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:802
msgid "rtr-listen"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:800
msgid ""
"An array of string values each providing the address and port which the "
"RTR daemon should listen on in TCP mode. Address and port should be "
"separated by a colon. IPv6 address should be enclosed in square brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:807
msgid "http-listen"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:805
msgid ""
"An array of string values each providing the address and port which the "
"HTTP service should listen on. Address and port should be separated by a "
"colon. IPv6 address should be enclosed in square brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:813
msgid "listen-systemd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:810
msgid ""
"The RTR TCP listening socket will be acquired from systemd via socket "
"activation. Use this option together with systemd's socket units to allow"
" Routinator running as a regular user to bind to the default RTR port "
"323."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:819
msgid "refresh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:816
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying the number of seconds Routinator should wait "
"between consecutive validation runs in server mode. The next validation "
"run will happen earlier, if objects expire earlier. The default is 600 "
"seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:824
msgid "retry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:822
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying the number of seconds an RTR client is "
"requested to wait after it failed to receive a data set. The default is "
"600 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:831
msgid "expire"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:827
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying the number of seconds an RTR client is "
"requested to use a data set if it cannot get an update before throwing it"
" away and continuing with no data at all. The default is 7200 seconds if "
"it cannot get an update before throwing it away and continuing with no "
"data at all. The default is 7200 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:835
msgid "history-size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:834
msgid ""
"An integer value specifying how many change sets Routinator should keep "
"in RTR server mode. The default is 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:839
msgid "pid-file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:838
msgid ""
"A string value containing a path pointing to the PID file to be used in "
"daemon mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:843
msgid "working-dir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:842
msgid ""
"A string value containing a path to the working directory for the daemon "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:847
msgid "chroot"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:846
msgid ""
"A string value containing the path any daemon process should use as its "
"root directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:850
msgid "user"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:850
msgid "A string value containing the user name a daemon process should run as."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:853
msgid "group"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:853
msgid "A string value containing the group name a daemon process should run as."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:863
msgid "tal-label"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:856
msgid ""
"An array containing arrays of two string values mapping the name of a TAL"
" file (without the path but including the extension) as given by the "
"first string to the name of the TAL to be included where the TAL is "
"referenced in output as given by the second string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:861
msgid ""
"If the options missing or if a TAL isn't mentioned in the option, "
"Routinator will construct a name for the TAL by using its file name "
"(without the path) and dropping the extension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:866
msgid "HTTP Service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:867
msgid ""
"Routinator can provide an HTTP service allowing to fetch the Validated "
"ROA Payload in various formats. The service does not support HTTPS and "
"should only be used within the local network."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:871
msgid "The service only supports GET requests with the following paths:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:874
msgid ":command:`/metrics`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:874
msgid "Returns a set of monitoring metrics in the format used by Prometheus."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:879
msgid ":command:`/status`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:877
msgid ""
"Returns the current status of the Routinator instance. This is similar to"
" the output of the **/metrics** endpoint but in a more human friendly "
"format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:882
msgid ":command:`/version`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:882
msgid "Returns the version of the Routinator instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:889
msgid ":command:`/api/v1/validity/as-number/prefix`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:885
msgid ""
"Returns a JSON object describing whether the route announcement given by "
"its origin AS number and address prefix is RPKI valid, invalid, or not "
"found.  The returned object is compatible with that provided by the RIPE "
"NCC RPKI Validator. For more information, see "
"https://ripe.net/support/documentation/developer-documentation/rpki-"
"validator-api"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:892
msgid ":command:`/validity?asn=as-number&prefix=prefix`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:892
msgid "Same as above but with a more form-friendly calling convention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:894
msgid ""
"In addition, the current set of VRPs is available for each output format "
"at a path with the same name as the output format. E.g., the CSV output "
"is available at ``/csv``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:898
msgid ""
"These paths accept filter expressions to limit the VRPs returned in the "
"form of a query string. The field ``filter-asn`` can be used to filter "
"for ASNs and the field ``filter-prefix`` can be used to filter for "
"prefixes. The fields can be repeated multiple times."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:903
msgid ""
"This works in the same way as the options of the same name to the "
":subcmd:`vrps` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:907
msgid "Relaxed Validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:908
msgid ""
"The documents defining RPKI include a number of very strict rules "
"regarding the formatting of the objects published in the RPKI repository."
" However, because PRKI reuses existing technology, real-world "
"applications produce objects that do not follow these strict "
"requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:913
msgid ""
"As a consequence, a significant portion of the RPKI repository is "
"actually invalid if the rules are followed. We therefore introduce two "
"validation modes: strict and relaxed. Strict mode rejects any object that"
" does not pass all checks laid out by the relevant RFCs. Relaxed mode "
"ignores a number of these checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:919
msgid ""
"This memo documents the violations we encountered and are dealing with in"
" relaxed validation mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:937
msgid "Resource Certificates (:rfc:`6487`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:924
msgid ""
"Resource certificates are defined as a profile on the more general "
"Internet PKI certificates defined in :rfc:`5280`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:937
msgid "Subject and Issuer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:929
msgid ""
"The RFC restricts the type used for CommonName attributes to "
"PrintableString,  allowing only a subset of ASCII characters, while "
":rfc:`5280` allows a number of additional string types. At least one CA "
"produces resource certificates with Utf8Strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:934
msgid ""
"In relaxed mode, we will only check that the general structure of the "
"issuer and subject fields are correct and allow any number and types of "
"attributes. This seems justified since RPKI explicitly does not use these"
" fields."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:955
msgid "Signed Objects (:rfc:`6488`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:940
msgid ""
"Signed objects are defined as a profile on CMS messages defined in "
":rfc:`5652`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:955
msgid "DER Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:944
msgid ""
":rfc:`6488` demands all signed objects to be DER encoded while the more "
"general CMS format allows any BER encoding  --  DER is a stricter subset "
"of the more general BER. At least one CA does indeed produce BER encoded "
"signed objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:949
msgid "In relaxed mode, we will allow BER encoding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:951
msgid ""
"Note that this isn't just nit-picking. In BER encoding, octet strings can"
" be broken up into a sequence of sub-strings. Since those strings are in "
"some places used to carry encoded content themselves, such an encoding "
"does make parsing significantly more difficult. At least one CA does "
"produce such broken-up strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:958
msgid "Signals"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:962
msgid "SIGUSR1: Reload TALs and restart validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:960
msgid ""
"When receiving SIGUSR1, Routinator will attempt to reload the TALs and, "
"if that succeeds, restart validation. If loading the TALs fails, "
"Routinator will exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:965
msgid "Exit Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/routinator/manual-page.rst:966
msgid ""
"Upon success, the exit status 0 is returned. If any fatal error happens, "
"the exit status will be 1. Some commands provide a :option:`--complete` "
"option which will cause the exit status to be 2 if any of the rsync "
"commands to update the repository fail."
msgstr ""

